# 🎮 AI Rover: Data Collection Simulator

## 🎯 Purpose

This script (`Python_robot_simulator.py`) is a custom 2D simulation environment built to generate the training data required by the machine learning models.

Before the robot can autonomously avoid obstacles, it needs to learn from human demonstration. This simulator allows a user to manually drive a virtual robot around a custom obstacle course. As you drive, the system continuously records the robot's sensor readings and your steering decisions, compiling them into the `rover_navigation_dataset.csv` file used in the main ML pipeline.

---

## 🚀 How It Works

- **The Environment** — The simulator generates an 800×600 pixel arena containing various hardcoded obstacles, including outer walls, distinct rooms, and freestanding pillars.
- **Virtual Sensors (Raycasting)** — The robot is equipped with three simulated LiDAR/distance sensors pointing Left (−45°), Front (0°), and Right (+45°). These sensors cast visible rays (up to 300 pixels) to measure the distance to the nearest obstacle.
- **Data Logging** — To prevent data bloat and redundant samples, the script only records data every 5 frames, and only when the robot is actively moving forward.
- **Label Mapping** — Keyboard inputs are mapped directly to the `action` column in the dataset:

| Key Input | `action` Value | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| No steering / forward only | `0` | Moving forward |
| Left Arrow | `1` | Turning left |
| Right Arrow | `2` | Turning right |

---

## 🛠️ Setup & Requirements

This simulator relies heavily on **Pygame** for rendering and event handling. Install it via pip:
```bash
pip install pygame
```

> **Note:** `math`, `csv`, and `sys` are built-in Python libraries and do not require manual installation.

---

## 💻 Usage Instructions

### 1. Run the Simulator

Execute the script from your terminal:
```bash
python Python_robot_simulator.py
```

### 2. Drive the Robot

| Key | Action |
|---|---|
| `↑` Up Arrow (hold) | Drive forward |
| `←` Left Arrow | Steer left |
| `→` Right Arrow | Steer right |

> **Tip:** Try to drive smoothly and safely around the walls. The better your human demonstration, the smarter your AI will be!

### 3. Save the Dataset

- Once you have navigated the course and generated enough scenarios (corners, straightaways, narrow passages), simply **close the Pygame window**.
- The script will automatically compile your session and output `rover_navigation_dataset.csv` into the same directory.
- The terminal will print exactly how many data samples were successfully collected.
